          "body": "The most theologically distinctive contribution the Chronicler makes in this chapter (absent from the briefer parallel in 2 Samuel 8:8) is the editorial note in verse 8: the bronze taken from Hadadezer's cities of Tibhath and Cun was the very bronze 'with which Solomon made the bronze sea and the pillars and the bronze utensils.' This forward-looking gloss is the Chronicler's signature interpretive move throughout the David narrative — every major action of David's reign is narrated with one eye on the Temple. David cannot build the Temple (1 Chronicles 22:8), but his wars are pre-building it. The gold of the shields (v. 7), the gold and silver of Tou's diplomatic gift (v. 10), and the accumulated spoils of six nations consecrated in verse 11 — all of it is heading toward Jerusalem, toward the sanctuary, toward the worship of the God who granted the victories in the first place. The Chronicler's readers, who had just rebuilt a modest Second Temple (Ezra 3-6), are reminded that even that Temple's predecessor was funded by extraordinary divine providence through conquest."
